Before she left the island, Elsa visited the local prison, where she learned about the last inmate of Spandau jail in Berlin. She also discovered that Eddie Murphy's first movie was "48 Hrs."

As Elsa boarded her plane back home, she felt grateful for all the new knowledge she had gained on her adventure. She knew that she would always cherish the memories of her trip to the remote island in the Pacific Ocean.

Story:
Tommy Pickles was a curious toddler who loved to learn new things. One day, he overheard his parents talking about the shipping forecast area directly north of German Bight. Intrigued, he asked his grandpa Lou to tell him more about it. 

As they sat together, Lou noticed that Tommy was counting on his fingers. "What are you doing, kiddo?" he asked. "Trying to remember what 1009 is in Roman numerals," replied Tommy. Lou chuckled and taught him the answer.

As they continued listening to the radio, they heard a news report about the Iron Chancellor, Otto von Bismarck. Tommy didn't understand who he was, but he knew it must be important.

That night, Tommy's parents were watching a movie about the Russian Revolution. "Tsar Nicholas I abdicated in 1917, just like King Constantine I of Greece," said Tommy's dad. "Whoa, I didn't know that," said Tommy.

The next day at school, Tommy's teacher was reciting Julius Caesar's last words as "Et Tu Brute". Tommy was fascinated and couldn't wait to tell his grandpa Lou.

As they watched a movie that night, Tommy recognized the character played by Mel Gibson as William Wallace in Braveheart. "Kenneth Branagh played the same character in a different movie called Henry V," said Lou.

As the movie ended, they saw the United Artists logo on the screen. "Did you know that the original United Artists film studio was founded in 1919 by D.W. Griffith, Mary Pickford, Douglas Fairbanks and Charlie Chaplin?" asked Lou. Tommy was amazed and couldn't wait to learn more.

Story:
John was a car enthusiast who loved everything about cars, from their design to their performance. He was particularly fond of classic cars and had been saving up for years to buy one. Finally, he found the perfect vintage car and bought it without a second thought.

Little did John know that there was an infamous car thief in town who had his eyes set on John's car. The car thief had a reputation for stealing cars and had even been caught stealing horses in the past. In fact, he was hanged for horse-stealing in April 1739.

The car thief, whose name was Jack, had a plan to steal John's car. He knew that John was a car lover and would never leave his car unattended. So, he decided to break into John's garage and steal the car in the dead of the night.

However, John was not one to be taken lightly. He had installed the latest security system in his garage and had even hired a guard to keep an eye on his car. But Jack was determined to get his hands on the car and was willing to do whatever it takes.

One night, John heard a noise coming from his garage and rushed to investigate. He was shocked to find Jack trying to break into his car. John quickly called the police, and Jack was arrested.

It turned out that Jack was a turophile, a lover of cheese, and had been stealing cars to fund his cheese addiction. He was sentenced to prison for his crimes.

John was relieved that his car was safe and took it out for a drive to celebrate. As he drove down the road, he realized that he was listening to the Halle Orchestra, which was founded in Manchester, the same city where he had bought his car. He smiled to himself and thought about how lucky he was to have found his dream car and to have protected it from the clutches of a car thief.

As he drove, he passed a group of hurling players, and he wondered how many players were on the field in a hurling team. But he didn't dwell on it for too long and continued to enjoy his drive, knowing that his car was safe and sound.

Plan:
Bolt, a young man from Sheffield, UK, is a huge fan of movies and trivia. He spends most of his time watching films and reading about their production. One day, he decides to participate in a local pub quiz, hoping to win the grand prize. However, he soon realizes that the questions are much harder than he anticipated. Bolt must use his knowledge and quick thinking to answer the following questions: How many male strippers perform on stage together in the 1997 film ‘The Full Monty’? The 2009 film ‘The Hangover’ is set in which city? In 1996, Dolly the Sheep was successfully cloned in which European country? ‘Steps in Time’ is a 1959 autobiography by which American singer/actor? Historical figures John Rann, John MacLaine, James Hind and Claude Duval were all notorious what? In the US television series ‘Friends’, what is Joey’s surname? Which US comedian/actor is credited with saying ‘A man is only as old as the woman he feels’? ‘Be the best’ is the official motto of which of the British armed forces? The feathers of which bird are said to bring bad luck if they are brought into the house? What is the name of the official British coronation crown?

Story:
Bolt had always been a movie buff, and he prided himself on his knowledge of film trivia. He spent most of his free time watching movies and reading about their production. One day, he heard about a local pub quiz that offered a grand prize of £500. Bolt was excited at the prospect of winning the prize, so he decided to participate.

The quiz was much harder than Bolt anticipated. The questions were tricky, and he struggled to keep up with the other contestants. However, he refused to give up. He knew that he had a wealth of knowledge about movies, and he was determined to use it to his advantage.

The first question was about the 1997 film ‘The Full Monty’. Bolt knew the answer immediately. "Six," he said confidently. The quizmaster nodded, impressed.

The next question was about the 2009 film ‘The Hangover’. Bolt had seen the movie several times, so he knew the answer without hesitation. "Las Vegas," he said.

The third question was about Dolly the Sheep, the first mammal to be cloned from an adult cell. Bolt remembered reading about it in a science magazine. "Scotland," he said.

The fourth question was about ‘Steps in Time’, a 1959 autobiography by Sammy Davis Jr. Bolt had never read the book, but he knew that Davis was a famous singer and actor. "Sammy Davis Jr.," he said confidently.

The fifth question was about historical figures John Rann, John MacLaine, James Hind, and Claude Duval. Bolt had no idea who they were, but he guessed that they were notorious criminals. "Highwaymen," he said.

The sixth question was about the US television series ‘Friends’. Bolt had watched every episode of the show, so he knew the answer. "Tribbiani," he said.

The seventh question was about a quote by US comedian/actor Groucho Marx. Bolt had heard the quote before, but he couldn't remember who said it. He took a guess. "Groucho Marx," he said.

The eighth question was about the official motto of the British armed forces. Bolt had no idea, but he guessed that it was the Royal Marines. "Royal Marines," he said.

The ninth question was about a bird whose feathers were said to bring bad luck if brought into the house. Bolt had never heard of such a thing, but he guessed that it was a crow. "Crow," he said.

The final question was about the name of the official British coronation crown. Bolt had seen pictures of the crown in history books. "St. Edward's Crown," he said.

Bolt waited anxiously as the quizmaster tallied up the scores. When the results were announced, Bolt was thrilled to hear that he had won the grand prize of £500. He had used his knowledge and quick thinking to answer all ten questions correctly, and he was proud of himself for doing so. From that day on, Bolt knew that he could accomplish anything he set his mind to.
